segments.text: Background information on Travis Bell Bryan Jr.
He was born on April 14, 1922, in Houston, Texas.
His wife's given and maiden name is Norma Norman.
His children are Travis B. Bryan III and Timothy N. Bryan.
His present position is the chairman of the board of the First National Bank of Bryan.
He was educated at Stephen F. Austin High School in Bryan, Texas.
He got his BS in business administration from Texas A&M University.
His church membership is the First Baptist Church of Bryan, Texas.
His honor recognitions are president of Bryan College Station Chamber of Commerce in 1960, chairman of the Bryan United Fund in 1957, 58, 69, and 74,
He was also the chairman of the Salvation Army Unit of Bryan, board of directors of Bryan City Mission, president of the Knife and Fork Club in 1959,
Commander of American Legion for two years.
President of Bryan YMCA.
Advisor and board of the Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in 69, 70, and 71.
He's a member of the Masonic Lodge and 32 Degree Mason.
Board of Directors of Bryan Public Library.
School board of Bryan Public Schools.
Board of Directors, Mary Hardin, Baylor, and Belton, Texas.
And the president of the Bryan City Mission and winner of 97 golf tournaments.
As I understand it, it was your great-grandfather that founded Bryan and gave land for it to be settled upon?
That's right, yes.
Once upon a time, there was a man named Moses Austin who lived in Missouri and had an idea of colonizing Texas.
which was a wilderness at that time, and a part of Mexico, a province of Mexico.
Before Moses Austin could realize his dream of the colonization of Texas, he died.
He had a son named Stephen F. Austin,
who later became known as the father of Texas.
Stephen F. Austin went to Mexico and prevailed on the Mexican government to appoint him as the impresario to colonize Texas and to fulfill, therefore, his father's dream.

So Austin then came back to Texas, even after he spent some time in jail in Mexico, prompted by this wild dream of his, so to speak, came back to Texas and went about the business of colonizing the state or the area.
His sister, Emily Austin,
had married a fellow named James Bryan, and they had three sons, William Joel Bryan, Moses Austin Bryan, and Guy M. Bryan.
Well, each of these nephews of Stephen F. Austin came into consideration for some land.
The particular land that we're sitting on here today called Bryan, Texas, was given to William Joel Bryan, who is my great-grandfather, incidentally.
And he then set up a township and named it after himself, Bryan, Texas.

There was a community at Boonville, which is a few miles to the east of us, inhabited by a few citizens, and he moved them over here and laid out the town and prevailed on the railroad to come on down from Marlin, I believe.
Marlin, Texas was as far as it came at the time.
prevailed on the railroad to bring its tracks on down to Bryan.
And incidentally, he rode the cow catcher on the engine into town on the first trip by the railroad into Bryan.
He named Bryan as the county seat for the county of Brazos.
And he sold the land up where the courthouse is today to the county for $1.
In his efforts to get the railroad to come through town, he gave the land for that.
He sold the railroad, the property, the right of way for $1 for the tracks to go on.
And he did all in his power to
organized a town which he did and today is named Bryan, Texas.
That's really it in a nutshell is how it all happened and I think that
the A&M University was organized by the state of Texas when his brother, Guy Bryan, was Speaker of the House of Representatives of the state.
So I realized that with all this and 15 cents, I can get a cup of coffee.
I am very proud of the effect on this area that my relatives had.
I don't know what else you might want to know about it, but that, as I said a moment ago, is it in a nutshell, Mr. Lippincott.
Well, has there been any disasters or anything since you've been here, like yellow fever in 1867 or something like that, epidemics?
No, I don't know of any epidemics or any disasters other than the weather.
We've had a tornado or two.
I don't think there's been any kind of disaster in this area, to my knowledge.
It's been a real good place to live.
It's a good place to rear a family.
It's known as a city of churches and schools.
We have a fine school system.
every kind of religious denomination you can think of here.
The fact that the greatest university in the land, Texas A&M is next door is quite attractive to people living in this area.
It offers advantages that other communities do not have.
Incidentally,
Bryan College Station today is the fastest growing city in Texas.
And Texas A&M University is the fastest growing university in the nation.
So the little thing started by the Bryans many years ago has grown to a burgeoning community and one that we can all be proud of.
and that uh one that seems to be destined for tremendous success in the future that's it thank you very much
